
Problem summary
When broad “require MFA” Conditional Access policies are applied directly to the Microsoft Intune and Microsoft Intune Enrollment app, conditional access policies interfere with the background token and enrollment flows that Windows relies on especially for hybrid Entra ID joined devices. This can block PRT refresh, which in turn causes the familiar “Problem with your work or school account” / “Access work or school – Needs attention” messages and ongoing device sync and compliance issues. 

Conditional Access Design for Intune Enrollment and Hybrid-Joined Devices

By excluding Microsoft Intune (0000000a-0000-0000-c000-000000000000) and Microsoft Intune Enrollment (d4ebce55-015a-49b5-a083-c84d1797ae8c) from our broad MFA Conditional Access policies, we keep the device join, enrollment, and sync pipeline running smoothly. These services handle core background operations for hybrid Entra ID joined devices, including issuing and refreshing the Primary Refresh Token (PRT). Allowing them to operate without generic MFA requirements significantly reduces enrollment failures, prevents the familiar “Problem with your work or school account” prompts, and improves overall device compliance and sync reliability.
At the same time, we’re not weakening security. Instead of forcing MFA on these background flows, we apply MFA where it delivers the most value: at the device registration user action and on business applications that access corporate data. This approach maintains strong access controls while preserving a stable PRT, providing better user experience, and ensuring devices are properly hybrid-joined and compliant before they’re granted access.

Note: Excluding Microsoft Intune (0000000a-0000-0000-c000-000000000000) and
Microsoft Intune Enrollment (d4ebce55-015a-49b5-a083-c84d1797ae8c) from a broad
“All cloud apps – Require MFA” policy does not remove MFA requirements for administrators in the Intune / Entra admin portals. Admin MFA should be enforced by separate, dedicated Conditional Access policies that target admin roles and admin portals. This repository focuses only on refining the tenant-wide MFA policy to avoid breaking device enrollment and PRT flows, not on weakening existing admin protections.




Protecting Excluded Apps with Enrollment Controls
While the Intune Enrollment service and Microsoft Intune applications are excluded from our broad MFA Conditional Access policies, they are not left exposed. These exclusions are paired with a strict control that blocks personal Windows device enrollments, ensuring that only corporate-owned, IT-approved Windows devices can use these services. In practice, this prevents an attacker from taking stolen credentials, enrolling a personal laptop or VM, and leveraging the exempted Intune apps to obtain a “trusted” or compliant endpoint. All enrollment activity and ongoing use of the Intune and Intune Enrollment services must originate from devices that have passed through our managed provisioning paths (Autopilot, hybrid join, etc.). This combination keeps background PRT and enrollment flows healthy, while maintaining tight governance over which devices are allowed to benefit from these Conditional Access exclusions.

Threat Mitigation for Intune Conditional Access Exclusions
While the Intune Enrollment and Microsoft Intune applications would be excluded from our broad MFA Conditional Access policies to preserve reliable PRT and enrollment flows, they are not an avenue for attackers to hide behind. As part of this design, we are currently blocking personal Windows device enrollment, requiring Intune administration to go through PIM activation with MFA from a compliant device, and we are restricting Microsoft Graph access to compliant endpoints. Under this model, an attacker would not be able to simply enroll a rogue device and rely on the excluded Intune apps to gain a trusted foothold; instead, they would need to compromise an existing compliant device or privileged identity, which is where our PIM, Conditional Access, and monitoring controls would be focused.

